  .box
    %article.main-column.no-left
      .row
        %h4 Prototyping
        .col-2
          .column.p-top-m
            %figure.image-wrapper.ios-h
              = image_tag("nixle/nixle-ios-flinto.gif")
              %figcaption
          .column
            %p
              Using <a href="https://www.flinto.com/" target="_blank">Flinto</a>, I created a preliminary prototype of the iOS application. It features the core information architecture in the <a href="https://developer.apple.com/library/ios/documentation/userexperience/conceptual/mobilehig/Bars.html#//apple_ref/doc/uid/TP40006556-CH12-SW52" target="_blank">tab bar</a>.
            %p
              One of my biggest learnings was that <strong>I should have built
              lower-fidelity screens for this interactive prototype</strong>,
              perhaps even possibly with pencil and paper. It was too early to
              be thinking about visual design while we were still figuring out
              the information architecture.
            %p
              Furthermore, my teammate who is an iOS developer gave me feedback
              that it's more ideal to test the interactive prototype in
              low-fidelity to assess the complexity of the proposal before
              polishing the "look & feel".

  .box
    %article.main-column.no-left
      .row
        %h4 Using card sorting to sort out uncertainties
        %p
          During this point in the project, I felt <i>very</i> uncertain about
          the viability of two features: 1) "trackify" and 2) allowing users to
          create alerts. In order to test my hypothesis that these features
          would prove mentally challenging to new application users, I ran a <a href="http://robots.thoughtbot.com/card-sorting" target="_blank">card sorting</a>.
        %p
          This exercise confirmed my hypothesis that these features would be
          mentally complexing to new users, and I was able to defend the
          product decision to not have these two features be in MVP with this
          evidence.
